<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n06150d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n06" href="#n06150d">N06 (VI.B.11)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n06all.htm#n06150d"> 150(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> catechist / &mdash;umen / &mdash;ism</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">The word <mark>Catechism</mark> is of Greek origin, to sound in the ear, to resound; it does not occur in classical authors, and is commonly used to signify a book containing instruction in the principles of the Christian Faith. The teacher by this ancient method, which was a universal practice in the early Church, is called a <mark>Catechist</mark>; the taught, a <mark>Catechumen</mark>. <small> Anonymous, <a name="ATCC" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#ATCC"><cite title="source">Analysis of the Church Catechism</cite></a> (1879) 5</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
